% @PACKAGE_NAME@(n) @PACKAGE_VERSION@ | Unix Domain Sockets for Tcl
% Cyan Ogilvie
% @PACKAGE_VERSION@


# NAME

@PACKAGE_NAME@ - Communicate using unix domain sockets


## SYNOPSIS

**package require @PACKAGE_NAME@** ?@PACKAGE_VERSION@?

**unix_sockets::listen** *path* *accept_handler*\
**unix_sockets::connect** *path*


## DESCRIPTION

Unix domain sockets are a filesystem based IPC mechanism similar to IP
sockets, except that they can only be used by processes on the same
system.  This package provides a wrapper to use them from Tcl scripts.

The channels returned by these commands support the standard Tcl channel
operations: **read**, **puts**, **gets**, **flush**, **close**,
**chan configure**, **chan event**, etc.

**unix_sockets::listen** *path* *accept_handler*

:   Open a listening socket at *path*.  If *path* already exists, it is
    unlinked first.  You must have permission to create *path* in its
    parent directory.  When a client connects, *accept_handler* is
    invoked with the channel handle of the new client connection
    appended.  Returns the channel handle of the listening socket.

**unix_sockets::connect** *path*

:   Connect as a client to the unix domain socket at *path*.  Returns
    the channel handle for the new connection.


## EXAMPLES

A simple server that echoes back to the client the first line it sends,
then closes the socket:

```tcl
proc readable con {
    set msg [gets $con]
    puts $con $msg
    close $con
}

proc accept con {
    chan event $con readable [list readable $con]
}

set listen [unix_sockets::listen /tmp/example.socket accept]

vwait ::forever
```

A client that opens a socket, writes a line to it, waits for a response
and exits:

```tcl
proc readable con {
    set msg [gets $con]
    puts "got response: ($msg)"
    set ::done 1
}

set con [unix_sockets::connect /tmp/example.socket]
puts $con "hello, world"
flush $con
chan event $con readable [list readable $con]
vwait ::done
```


